ithmetic of probabilities and later also the mathematical theory of combinations and permutations. It is shown that almost all the conceptions of probability which are entertained today, as well as some of the enigmas which beset contemporary philosophers of probability and induction, are described in the rabbinic writings. Readers interested in the history of ideas and the philosophy of science, the development of logic and mathematics, as well as students of Jewish thought and medieval philosophy, will find much to engage their attention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematical statisticsxHistory. 0aMathematics, Jewish. 0aProbabilitiesxHistory. 0aRabbinical literature. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Theology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757458140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487574581423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487574581.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK